# This project uses .gitlabels <https://github.com/elliottcable/.gitlabels>
# to tag commits so humans can better understand the scope of changes, and 
# tools can help visualising changes.

# For further information around this, check our Git commit guidelines at:
# <https://github.com/ythecombinator/You-Dont-Know-X/CONTRIBUTING.md>

feat (new feature)
fix (bug fix)
docs (changes to documentation)
style (formatting, missing semi colons, etc; no code change)
refactor (refactoring production code)
test (adding missing tests, refactoring tests; no production code change)

- (new)             indicates new content or features are introduced
    - (unit)        a new post, paper, book etc. is introduced for an existing category
    - (category)    a new category/subcategory is introduced

- (fix)             indicates changes that fix outstanding problems, misconceptions etc.

- (style)           indicates a commit that only changes style guide of this document
- (doc)             indicates commits that change commentary, documentation etc.

- (chore)           updating project organization, automation etc.
